Verification and Cleanup
Verify all collections and clean up:

# Verify collections
echo "Verifying data integrity..."
for dir in ~/windows_collection/*/; do
    echo "Windows collection: $(basename "$dir")"
    ls -la "$dir"
done

for dir in ~/linux_collection/*/; do
    echo "Linux collection: $(basename "$dir")"
    ls -la "$dir"
done

# Optional cleanup
read -p "Do you want to clean up temporary files? (y/n): " cleanup
if [[ $cleanup == "y" ]]; then
    rm -rf /tmp/suspicious_dir
    rm -f /tmp/suspicious_connections.log
    rm -f /tmp/fake_hosts
    kill $(cat /tmp/suspicious_pid.txt 2>/dev/null) 2>/dev/null
    rm -f /tmp/suspicious_pid.txt
    echo "Cleanup completed"
fi
Conclusion
You have successfully completed live response data collection on both Windows and Linux endpoints. This lab demonstrated:

Cross-platform incident response techniques using open-source tools
Data collection methodologies for different operating systems
Comparative analysis of Windows and Linux artifacts
Identification of suspicious activities and indicators of compromise
The skills learned in this lab are essential for incident responders and digital forensics professionals who must quickly assess and collect evidence from compromised systems. Understanding the differences between Windows and Linux artifacts helps in developing comprehensive response strategies and ensures critical evidence is not overlooked during investigations.

Key takeaways include the importance of systematic data collection, proper documentation, and the ability to adapt collection techniques based on the target operating system's unique characteristics and available artifacts.
